{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524385"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13987"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13987"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.22,0.04,0.15,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6621"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101444"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6621"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13987"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83883"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44966"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101444"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She does not have any concerns, no particular symptoms and is currently enjoying good health. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She does not smoke and drinks one or two glasses of wine at weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A full physical examination is performed and no abnormalities are found. Her BMI is 22 kg/m2. A photograph of her neck is shown (Image), revealing a soft, non-tender swelling in the left submandibular region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A normal submandibular gland","Sialadenitis","Metastatic deposit","Lymphoma","Sjogren\u0027s syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a visible swelling in the left submandibular region, which is most likely a \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal submandibular gland\u003C/strong\u003E. It is important to recognise that in individuals with a normal or low BMI, the submandibular glands can be visible, especially when the neck is extended. This patient\u0027s BMI of 22 kg/m2 is within the normal range, making this a plausible explanation for the visible gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESialadenitis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to inflammation of the salivary gland, which would typically present with pain, tenderness, redness, and swelling of the affected gland. It is often associated with infection, obstruction (such as a calculus), or autoimmune conditions. The absence of any symptoms, particularly pain or tenderness, makes this diagnosis unlikely in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic deposit\u003C/strong\u003E in a lymph node is an important consideration in any neck swelling, even in asymptomatic patients. However, metastatic deposits are usually firm, fixed, and may be associated with other symptoms or a known primary malignancy. The lack of symptoms and the normal physical examination make this less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present as painless lymphadenopathy, but is usually associated with other symptoms such as night sweats, weight loss, or fatigue. Additionally, lymphoma typically involves multiple lymph nodes rather than an isolated swelling. The patient\u0027s good health and lack of systemic symptoms make lymphoma an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESjogren\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune condition characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth due to lymphocytic infiltration of exocrine glands. While it can cause enlargement of salivary glands, it typically affects the parotid glands bilaterally rather than a unilateral submandibular gland. Patients with Sjogren\u0027s syndrome usually present with symptoms of dryness, and often have other autoimmune conditions. The absence of these symptoms makes this diagnosis unlikely in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile it is crucial to consider and exclude pathological causes for any neck swelling, it is equally important to recognise normal anatomical variations. In this case, the asymptomatic nature of the swelling, its soft consistency, mobility with swallowing, and the patient\u0027s normal BMI all support the diagnosis of a visible normal submandibular gland. However, if there were any doubts or concerns, further investigations such as ultrasound or fine-needle aspiration could be considered to definitively exclude pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Normal submandibular glands can be visible in individuals with a normal or low BMI, especially when the neck is extended.","Submandibular gland swelling due to pathology is often associated with symptoms such as pain or discomfort, particularly after meals.","Malignant processes in the neck should always be considered and excluded, even in asymptomatic patients."],"references":["Wilson KF, Meier JD, Ward PD. Salivary Gland Disorders. Am Fam Physician. 2014; 89:882-88."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83883"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13987"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20882"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20882"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Q5HDzfJfwjsn9MjVpDQeRGWf12jLOa.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Q5HDzfJfwjsn9MjVpDQeRGWf12jLOa.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83883"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T23:11:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T23:12:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6621"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101444"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4959","links":{"se